node.text: You and your partner should be each other’s biggest supports - but not each other’s biggest enablers. Your partner should know what your goal is and help you see it through. When you’re low or frustrated your partner should be there to remind you of who you’re trying to become and that you can absolutely make it. But you have to welcome empathy over sympathy. You have to give them permission to help keep you focused and motivated. It doesn’t help for them to get angry or sad with you. It helps to be understood, absolutely, but when you fall, you don’t need someone to get on the floor with you, you need someone that can help you back up. If you want to learn more about this idea and many others, be sure to join @lisabilyeu and I for our YouTube show Relationship Theory. Link in bio.

node.title: When Your Partner Needs A Kick In The Ass

node.text:
Watching someone build themselves up from a loss is so powerful. ⁣
⁣
Why? Because it reminds us that it doesn’t matter where we start or how hard we fall. ⁣What matters is putting in the work to get better. ⁣
⁣
We are capable of such radical change, and there is a voice in our head screaming for us to push ourselves. ⁣
⁣
And when we listen to that voice and drag ourselves inch by inch towards the extraordinary our entire story about who we are changes.⁣

node.text: The passing of @trevormoawad is absolutely heartbreaking. We have all lost a powerful voice in personal development. The incredible legacy of mental resilience that he leaves behind for all of us, however, will continue to touch lives for a very long time to come. I’m honored to have had a chance to meet and interview him. He was truly legendary. To his family and loved ones, all of us here at @impacttheory send our most heartfelt condolences. With love and a heavy heart, Tom.

node.text: Money is the great facilitator, but it will not help you find fulfillment.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tom Bilyeu on September 15, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'IF YOU ARE THINKING: "I WANT TO REACH MY GOALS, BUT I CAN'T GET STARTED..." 北 READ BELOW'.

node.text:
I know this feeling all too well. Much of my 20s were spent fixated on my success but I was unable to do anything tangible to achieve that. I wanted to be a filmmaker and failed. I wanted to make a lot of money to finance my passion for filmmaking and failed at that too.

I wanted to reach my goals but I was stuck. I was stuck in a fixed mindset. I was stuck believing there wasn’t a path for me. I was stuck in my own fabricated narrative of what I was or wasn’t capable of.

This feeling of STUCK is truly pernicious. If you believe it, it will consume all your motivation. It will steal your ambitious goals and dash them on the rocks.
⁣
Being stuck feels like an insurmountable barrier, but that is an illusion! Often times we tell stories of a singular moment of inspiration that got a person unstuck and moving towards their goal. While this makes for a nice cathartic moment in a movie, it is not true.

Getting unstuck is a skill you can cultivate. It is, in truth, a way of using your brain to see the problem in a new way. Much like an athlete who can go from unable to run a mile to running a marathon, you can achieve what seemed at one point impossible by developing the necessary strength over a period of time.

If this at all is resonating with you or you simply want to add more tools to your skillset (which if you know me I am obsessed with building out more and more skills) then click the link in my bio and check out my 6 Steps To Getting Unstuck. This is one of my favorite classes from Impact Theory University and I want you to have it for free!

Now here comes the no BS. While the video is free, the work isn’t. I can show you the path, but you must walk it. I am here to help mentor you, but you must ask yourself honestly “AM I GOING TO PUT IN THE WORK?”  If that is a yes, smash that link and get your pen and paper ready because I know this will help you get closer to achieving your lofty goals and become legendary!

node.text: You and your partner should be each other’s biggest supports - but not each other’s biggest enablers. Your partner should know what your goal is and help you see it through. When you’re low or frustrated your partner should be there to remind you of who you’re trying to become and that you can absolutely make it. But you have to welcome empathy over sympathy. You have to give them permission to help keep you focused and motivated. It doesn’t help for them to get angry or sad with you. It helps to be understood, absolutely, but when you fall, you don’t need someone to get on the floor with you, you need someone that can help you back up. If you want to learn more about this idea and many others, be sure to join @lisabilyeu and I for our YouTube show Relationship Theory. Link in bio.

If you're ever spending more than 20% of your self-talk on negative shit, you're out of alignment. ⁣
⁣
And I think most people spend 90% of their time beating themselves up. ⁣
⁣
Take control of your inner dialog. ⁣
⁣
It's one of the most important things you could apply yourself to.

@theawkwardyeti

node.text:
I have been thinking a lot about decision-making. In fact some of you may have already participated in my Business Decision-Making Workshop. What this work has revealed to me is that much of my success has hinged on my ability to learn from mistakes and develop a system earned from those mistakes to make better decisions.

You cannot be a passive observer in your life (be it business, relationship, etc.). By adopting that mindset you will let the world happen to you. Your mistakes will be seen as punishments the world has set upon you. You must instead claim authority over your life and run headfirst into living. Make mistakes. Learn. Keep running forward. This is the only way I have discovered to get the life you want.

🖊 @paulocoelho
